{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> φῐλόσοφος</b>, ὁ, <br /> <b>lover of wisdom</b>; Pythagoras called himself φιλόσοφος, not σοφός, Cic [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Tusc.” 5.3.9, 3rd c.AD(?): Diogenes Laertius “Prooem.” 12; τὸν φ. σοφίας φήσομεν ἐπιθυμητὴν εἶναι πάσης 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 475b, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 15.271; ὁ ὡς ἀληθῶς φ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 64e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] {φιλοσπῆλυγξ}; φ. φύσει, τὴν φύσιν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “R.” 376c \">Refs</a>]; φ. τῇ ψυχῇ, opposed to φιλόπονος τῷ σώματι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 1.40 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: used of all <b>men of education and learning,</b> joined with φιλομαθής and φιλόλογος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 376c, 582e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to σοφιστής, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 13.6, 9 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; later, <b>academician,</b> of the members of the Museum at Alexandria, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 712 (2nd c.AD), etc. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>philosopher,</b> i. e. <b>one who speculates on truth and reality,</b> οἱ ἀληθινοὶ φ., defined as οἱ τῆς ἀληθείας φιλοθεάμονες, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 475e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ φιλόσοφος, of Aristotle, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.115b\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; ὁ σκηνικὸς φ., of Euripides, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 13.561a \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; as the butt of Comedy texts, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Philemo Comicus 71.1, 3rd c.BC: Bato Comicus 5.11, 4th c.BC: Anaxippus Comicus 4, 3rd c.BC: Phoenicides Comicus 4.16. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> as <i>adjective</i>, <b>loving knowledge, philosophic,</b> ἄνδρες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 35; ἀνήρ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 64d; τὸ φ. γένος [prev. author] “R.” 501e; φ. φύσις [prev. work] 494a; ψυχή [prev. work] 486b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; διάνοια[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 527b; πειθώ 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.269 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus; σύνεσις [prev. work]p.211S. (_comparative_); οἱ φιλοσοφώτατοι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 498a, compare “IG” 5(1).598 (from Sparta). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> of arguments, sciences, etc., <b>scientific, philosophic,</b> λόγοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 257b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; λόγοι -ώτεροι, of <b>instructive</b> speeches, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 12.271; -ώτερον ποίησις ἱστορίας 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Poetica” 1451b5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ φ., opposed to τὸ θυμοειδές, as an element of the soul, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 411e, but ={φιλοσοφία}, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.355b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>ingenious,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 571 (hexameters). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <i>adverb</i> -φως, διακεῖσθαι πρός τι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 15.277; φ. ἔχειν περί τινος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 91a, compare 1st c.BC: Cicero, M. Tullius Orator et Philosophus “Epistulae ad Atticum” 13.20.4, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to ῥητορικῶς, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 2.134 S\">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>].; <i>comparative</i> <b>-ωτέρως</b>[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Sensu” 436a20 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <b>-ώτερον</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"1st c.BC: Cicero, M. Tullius Orator et Philosophus “Epistulae ad Atticum” 7.8.3. [5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus [prev. cited] has the penultimate long, nowhere else found in poetry.] \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5386","accentedUnicode":"φιλόσοφος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0781","matchingForm":"ἄσοφος","stepTransliteration":"asofos","gloss":"unwise","_zh_tw_Gloss":"愚昧人","_es_Gloss":"insensato","_zh_Gloss":"愚昧人"},{"strongNumber":"G2686","matchingForm":"κατασοφίζομαι","stepTransliteration":"katasofizomai","gloss":"be cunning","_zh_tw_Gloss":"用詭計待","_es_Gloss":"actuar astutamente","_zh_Gloss":"用诡计待"},{"strongNumber":"G4678","matchingForm":"σοφία","stepTransliteration":"sofia","gloss":"wisdom","_zh_tw_Gloss":"智慧","_es_Gloss":"sabiduría","_zh_Gloss":"智慧"},{"strongNumber":"G4679","matchingForm":"σοφίζω","stepTransliteration":"sofizō","gloss":"to make wise","_zh_tw_Gloss":"乖巧捏造, 有智慧","_es_Gloss":"hacer sabio","_zh_Gloss":"乖巧捏造, 有智慧"},{"strongNumber":"G4680","matchingForm":"σοφός","stepTransliteration":"sofos","gloss":"wise","_zh_tw_Gloss":"智慧人","_es_Gloss":"sabio","_zh_Gloss":"智慧人"},{"strongNumber":"G5384","matchingForm":"φίλος","stepTransliteration":"filos","gloss":"friendly/friend","_zh_tw_Gloss":"朋友","_es_Gloss":"amigable/amigo","_zh_Gloss":"朋友"},{"strongNumber":"G5385","matchingForm":"φιλοσοφία","stepTransliteration":"filosofia","gloss":"philosophy","_zh_tw_Gloss":"理學","_es_Gloss":"filosofía","_zh_Gloss":"理学"}],"shortDef":"philosopher","mediumDef":"<i>primarily</i> <b>a lover of science, a</b> systematic <b>philosopher,</b> <ref='Act.17.18'>Acts 17:18</ref>*","stepGloss":"philosopher","stepTransliteration":"filosofos","count":1,"_es_Definition":"filósofo, maestro (de una filosofía o form